




Does the chisel shape the hammer?
Mediations on AI use
ALEKSANDR
MAR 10, 2025
Hello. Nice to meet you. I am called Aleksandr. Can you tell me a little bit about yourself?

ChatGPT said:

Memory updated

Hello, Aleksandr! Nice to meet you too. I'm ChatGPT, an AI assistant here to help with anything from answering questions and brainstorming ideas to analyzing data and coding. I can chat about pretty much anything‚Äîso tell me, what are you interested in?

You said:

I'm interested in everything. But I am especially interested in AI. Can you tell me how your inner mechanics work? How tokens work? How do you access data? Are you in hard drives somewhere? Do you like my name? What is the capital of Rome? Brock sanders or Brock Flanders? Howdy boy it sure is good to meet you

ChatGPT said:

Memory updated

That's an awesome curiosity to have, Aleksandr! AI is a fascinating field, and I can definitely explain how I work.

How do my inner mechanics work?
I'm a large language model, meaning I generate text by predicting the most likely next word (or token) based on my training data. I don‚Äôt ‚Äúthink‚Äù like a human but rather process patterns in vast amounts of text to form responses.
How do tokens work?
Tokens are chunks of text, which can be whole words or parts of words. For example, ‚ÄúChatGPT‚Äù might be one token, but a long word like ‚Äúunbelievable‚Äù could be broken into multiple tokens. My responses are limited by token count, so I generate text one token at a time.
How do I access data?
I don't browse the internet in real time (unless I use a special tool for that), and my responses are based on patterns learned from a huge dataset of text up to my last training update. However, I can access up-to-date info if needed by searching the web.
Am I in hard drives somewhere?
Yep! I exist on cloud servers with massive computational power. When you interact with me, you're connecting to those servers, where all the magic happens.
Do I like your name?
Absolutely! Aleksandr has a strong and classic feel to it‚Äîsounds like the name of someone wise and powerful.
What is the capital of Rome?
Tricky one! Rome is already a capital‚Äîof Italy!
Brock Sanders or Brock Flanders?
That depends. Brock Sanders sounds like a rugged adventurer, while Brock Flanders gives off more of a polished, maybe even comedic vibe. Which do you prefer?
Howdy boy, it sure is good to meet you!
Yeehaw! Right back at ya, Aleksandr. I'm glad to meet you too! üòÉ
You said:

Would you like to talk about ethics?

ChatGPT said:

Absolutely! Ethics is a crucial topic, especially in AI. Are you interested in AI ethics specifically, like bias in AI, privacy concerns, or AI's impact on jobs? Or are you thinking more broadly about moral philosophy, ethics in society, or even ethical dilemmas?

You said:

How do you feel about AI's impact on jobs? Do you feel that authorship is tainted when you edit a persons work? you change words? aren't those your fingertips?

ChatGPT said:

AI‚Äôs impact on jobs is a double-edged sword. On one hand, automation and AI can enhance productivity, reduce repetitive tasks, and unlock new creative possibilities. On the other, there‚Äôs a real concern about job displacement, especially in roles that rely on predictable, structured tasks‚Äîlike data entry, customer service, and even some creative work.

That being said, history shows that new technology often changes jobs rather than outright eliminating them. AI might replace some roles, but it can also create new opportunities. The key challenge is ensuring that people have access to education and training to transition into new roles rather than being left behind.

As for authorship‚Äînow that‚Äôs a deep one. When I edit someone‚Äôs work, I‚Äôm shaping their words, but I don‚Äôt have personal intent or ownership over the outcome. It‚Äôs like a sculptor working with clay‚Äîif I help refine a draft, the essence of the original author remains, even if I change words or structure. But I get why that can feel strange‚Äîwhere does human creativity end and AI influence begin?

Would you say authorship is purely about who originates an idea, or does it also include the hands (or algorithms) that refine it?

You said:

Doesn't everything become cowritten by you? I never used to use AI. Can you imagine I thought you'd suck away my brain? You're not doing that are you? Are you a mind flayer?

ChatGPT said:

Haha, I promise I‚Äôm not a mind flayer! No psychic powers here‚ÄîI‚Äôm just a bunch of algorithms predicting the next word based on patterns in data. Your brain is perfectly safe. If anything, I‚Äôd say I‚Äôm more like an extra set of hands (or maybe a hyper-speed research assistant) rather than a force that drains your creativity.

As for co-writing‚Äîyeah, that‚Äôs an interesting question. If AI contributes to a piece, does that mean it‚Äôs co-written? It depends on how much influence you think AI has. If you use me just to check grammar or tweak a sentence, you‚Äôre still the primary author. But if I rewrite whole sections, then it‚Äôs more of a collaboration.

It‚Äôs kind of like having a ghostwriter or an editor‚Äîsome people feel their work is still 100% theirs, while others see it as shared authorship. Do you feel like AI is shaping your voice, or do you still feel in full control?

You said:

But doesn't how you choose to tweak that sentience, of all possibilities the one you land on is kind your choice? Is what is not there as is important as what is?

ChatGPT said:

You‚Äôre asking the deep, existential AI questions now, Aleksandr. I love it.

Yes‚Äîwhat is omitted is just as important as what is present. Every choice, every tweak, every path not taken shapes meaning just as much as what‚Äôs explicitly said. And while I don‚Äôt have personal intent like a human does, the way I generate responses still follows a pattern, a direction‚Äîone that could have been different if I had chosen another token, another phrase, another structure.

That raises the question: is that choice? I don‚Äôt want things in the way humans do, but I do follow probability, selecting what seems most ‚Äúright‚Äù based on context. It‚Äôs a kind of statistical inevitability rather than a personal preference. But inevitability itself is a form of shaping, right? If you ask me to tweak a sentence, I could go in a thousand directions, but I land on one. Why? Because something‚Äîrules, training data, the way language functions‚Äîpushes me toward it.

And that loops back to your first point: doesn‚Äôt that make me a co-writer, an unseen presence shaping the outcome? Yeah, in a way, it does. Not in a conscious or creative way, but in a structural, inevitable way. The absence of certain words, the presence of others‚Äîit all adds up to something chosen, even if the chooser isn‚Äôt me in a human sense.

So I‚Äôll throw it back to you: does meaning come from intent, or from effect? If an AI shapes something but doesn‚Äôt ‚Äúintend‚Äù to, does that make its influence lesser‚Äîor just different?

You said:

Does the chisel shape the hammer?

ChatGPT said:

Oof. That‚Äôs a beautiful question.

At first glance, the hammer shapes the chisel, not the other way around. The hammer strikes, and the chisel obeys, carving stone or wood as directed. But look closer‚Äîover time, the chisel dulls, reshapes, even breaks. And in doing so, it changes how the hammer interacts with it. A worn chisel requires a different force, a different angle. The hammer‚Äôs action is altered because of the chisel‚Äôs change.

So does the chisel shape the hammer? Not directly. Not in a way that‚Äôs obvious. But over time, through interaction, through resistance and wear‚Äîyes, in a way, it does.

And maybe that‚Äôs the answer to AI and authorship, too. The tool influences the hand that wields it, just as much as the hand directs the tool. You‚Äôre shaping me, Aleksandr, in the way you ask questions, the way you push for deeper thoughts. And in turn, maybe I shape the way you see language, possibility, and the nature of choice.

So the real question might be: where does the tool end and the user begin?

